    "title_plain": "1987 &sect; 03",
    "content": "<div class=\"wp-caption alignright\" style=\"width: 385px\"><a href=\"http:\/\/www.history.navy.mil\/photos\/images\/g20000\/g27797c.htm\"><img src=\"https:\/\/img.skitch.com\/20110331-xe1r8j73c4kjyd74xnf53j4pfs.jpg\" alt=\"Woman using ditto machine in 1943\" width=\"375\" height=\"296\" \/><\/a><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">No, I&#8217;m not this old. But talking with a 25-year-old about dittos sure makes me feel like it. (Photo from the Navy Historical Center.)<\/p><\/div>\n<p>The lowly classroom handout is like a radar gun for the speed of change. I&#8217;m <!-- a href=\"http:\/\/alexlov.es\/1971\" -->not even 40 (yet)<!-- \/a -->, and I can play a very respectable game of &#8220;when I was a boy&#8230;.&#8221; OK, so sniffing mimeos isn&#8217;t quite as dramatic as walking three miles to school through the proverbial snowdrifts. But when my mother was 39, there were only three everyday technologies that had become obsolete in her lifetime: passenger ships, telegrams and pantyhose.<\/p>\n",
