    "title": "Listening to the Voice That Says It&#039;s OK to Be Online &sect; 2",
    "title_plain": "Listening to the Voice That Says It&#039;s OK to Be Online &sect; 2",
    "content": "<p><em>The King and I<\/em> was the beginning of a lifelong obsession with musicals, and as I learned more about their history I heard lots of people mourn the advent of amplification. Miles Kreuger, a musical theater historian I interviewed for my college radio show, talked longingly about hearing <!-- a class=\"zem_slink\" title=\"Gertrude Lawrence\" rel=\"lastfm\" href=\"http:\/\/www.last.fm\/music\/Gertrude%2BLawrence\" -->Gertrude Lawrence<!-- \/a --> <strong>(REFERENCE ICON) <a class=\"zem_slink\" title=\"Gertrude Lawrence\" href=\"http:\/\/www.last.fm\/music\/Gertrude%2BLawrence\" rel=\"lastfm\">Gertrude Lawrence<\/a> was a star of London and Broadway musicals in the 1930s and 1940s.<\/strong> in the original production of <em>The King and I<\/em>. She had a small voice, he said, so everybody quieted down and actually listened. If Gertrude Lawrence could be heard, he said, anyone can be heard without a microphone.<\/p>\n",
    "excerpt": "The King and I was the beginning of a lifelong obsession with musicals, and as I learned more about their history I heard lots of people mourn the advent of amplification. Miles Kreuger, a musical theater historian I interviewed for &hellip; <a href=\"http:\/\/book.hyko.org\/1970-10-02\/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&rarr;<\/span><\/a>",
