    "title": "Listening to the Voice That Says It&#039;s OK to Be Online &sect; 3",
    "title_plain": "Listening to the Voice That Says It&#039;s OK to Be Online &sect; 3",
    "content": "<p>For all the mystique surrounding old-style, unamplified shows, I never felt like I was missing much. Then in 2002, I saw <!-- THIS LINK OUTDATED a class=\"zem_slink\" title=\"Barbara Cook\" rel=\"myspaceeverything\" href=\"http:\/\/www.myspace.com\/everything\/barbara-cook\"-->Barbara Cook<!-- \/a --> at Lincoln Center. <strong>(REFERENCE ICON) <a href=\"http:\/\/www.sjsondheim.com\/centersondheim.html\">Kennedy Center Sondheim Celebration<\/a><\/strong> Cook is one of Broadway&#8217;s legendary divas, and in recent years has become a teacher and mentor to many up-and-coming performers. As a teacher of vocal technique, it makes sense that she would show off the way it should &#8212; or at least could &#8212; be done. For her final number, Cook sang <em>Anyone Can Whistle<\/em> without amplification.<\/p>\n",
