    "title": "Dittos Remind Us of the Pleasures of Obsolescence &sect; 2",
    "title_plain": "Dittos Remind Us of the Pleasures of Obsolescence &sect; 2",
    "content": "<p>You over-30s, take note of the fact that I had to explain this item from our collective archive. Over the past few years I&#8217;ve had a few thirtysomethings stare at me blankly when I made a passing reference to dittos. When I started school, the ditto and its ancestors had been captivating children for a full century: in fact, the mimeograph was invented by none other than <!-- a href=\"http:\/\/www.wired.com\/science\/discoveries\/news\/2008\/08\/dayintech_0808\" -->Thomas Edison in 1876<!-- \/a -->. <strong>(REFERENCE ICON) FURTHER READING\u00a0<a href=\"http:\/\/www.wired.com\/science\/discoveries\/news\/2008\/08\/dayintech_0808\">Run This Off on the Mimeo<\/a><\/strong>\u00a0But just ten years after I inhaled my first ditto in kindergarten, the ditto was more or less extinct (at least in North America), overtaken by the photocopier and the computer printer. Today&#8217;s 28-year-old American has never enjoyed the intoxicating high of methanol in the morning.<\/p>\n",
