    "title_plain": "Finding Our Online Elders &sect; 3",
    "content": "<p>In the online world, the closest we have to institutionalized &#8220;elders&#8221; are the people who serve as moderators in various kinds of online communities and conversations. They encourage us to make the most constructive contributions we can, inspire a community with engaging questions and conversations, and nudge us gently back in line if we step across the boundary of good behaviour. And with a little luck, they bring to that work the wisdom that comes from experience &#8212; not just with offline life, but with the specific dynamics and peculiarities of online interaction.<\/p>\n",
    "excerpt": "In the online world, the closest we have to institutionalized &#8220;elders&#8221; are the people who serve as moderators in various kinds of online communities and conversations. They encourage us to make the most constructive contributions we can, inspire a community &hellip; <a href=\"http:\/\/book.hyko.org\/1970-06-03\/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&rarr;<\/span><\/a>",
