    "title_plain": "Finding Our Online Elders &sect; 6",
    "content": "<p>In the early online groups, these initial roles were often called moderators (for Usenet and mailing lists) or hosts (for bulletin boards). Their primary functions were to enforce group norms and protocols, control access and determine which messages stayed and which were deleted. It was a gatekeeper function. The secondary role of stimulating conversation or interaction did not gain prominence until the emergence of \u201cvirtual communities,\u201d most often exemplified by the Well (www.well.com), with its well-defined volunteer hosts structure that exists to this day. The most important role for hosts on the Well was to foster the conversation, individual and group identity, and sociability of the topical areas for which they were responsible.<\/p>\n",
    "excerpt": "In the early online groups, these initial roles were often called moderators (for Usenet and mailing lists) or hosts (for bulletin boards). Their primary functions were to enforce group norms and protocols, control access and determine which messages stayed and &hellip; <a href=\"http:\/\/book.hyko.org\/1970-06-06\/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&rarr;<\/span><\/a>",
