    "title": "Finding Our Online Elders &sect; 9",
    "title_plain": "Finding Our Online Elders &sect; 9",
    "content": "<p>But we need our online elders more than ever &#8212; even if our &#8220;elders&#8221; are often the very youngest among us, those who have grown up online and are therefore familiar with its norms, technologies and pace. These baby elders can go along way to meeting the need we have for guidance as we enter new online spaces &#8212; spaces that may test the limits of our social skills and push the boundaries of our personal comfort zone. What they know about how to interact online, and especially, the ease and naturalness they bring to online interaction, can be valuable assets to those who are more tentative in their online interactions.<\/p>\n",
    "excerpt": "But we need our online elders more than ever &#8212; even if our &#8220;elders&#8221; are often the very youngest among us, those who have grown up online and are therefore familiar with its norms, technologies and pace. These baby elders &hellip; <a href=\"http:\/\/book.hyko.org\/1970-06-09\/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&rarr;<\/span><\/a>",
