    "title": "Finding Our Online Elders &sect; 11",
    "title_plain": "Finding Our Online Elders &sect; 11",
    "content": "<p>We need that kind of elder online, too: people with a wealth of life experience, much of it off line as well as on-, which can be transposed to the conflicts and opportunities of online conversation. Especially since these elders aren&#8217;t starting from scratch: their lifetime of wisdom builds on the knowledge and counsel they have received from their elders, tracing backwards in a chain of mentorship that goes all the way back to the dawn of humanity. Your great-great-great-great-grandmother might not have had a lot to tell you about how to use Twitter, but she would have had something to say about what it takes to connect with another person, to nurture a relationship, or to express your own ideas with care and compassion. Our chain of elders is how that wisdom gets passed along, until it&#8217;s available for us to bring online.<\/p>\n",
    "excerpt": "We need that kind of elder online, too: people with a wealth of life experience, much of it off line as well as on-, which can be transposed to the conflicts and opportunities of online conversation. Especially since these elders &hellip; <a href=\"http:\/\/book.hyko.org\/1970-06-11\/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&rarr;<\/span><\/a>",
