    "title": "Finding Our Online Elders &sect; 12",
    "title_plain": "Finding Our Online Elders &sect; 12",
    "content": "<p>But are we bringing that wisdom with us? Without our elders &#8212; our actual, chronically oldest members of society &#8212; we&#8217;re liable to lose much of that accumulated human wisdom as we move from offline to on. The fetishization of the Internet as a young person&#8217;s game, and in particular, the triumph of the &#8220;digital native&#8221; &#8212; the young person who has grown up online &#8212; means that older net-dwellers are often relegated to the margins. Far from being invited to moderate a conversation, or even respected informally as models for how to interact, they&#8217;re written off as people who &#8220;don&#8217;t get it&#8221; because they pre-date the norm of blogging your day, and may be openly critical of the wealth of personal detail that younger people post online.<\/p>\n",
    "excerpt": "But are we bringing that wisdom with us? Without our elders &#8212; our actual, chronically oldest members of society &#8212; we&#8217;re liable to lose much of that accumulated human wisdom as we move from offline to on. The fetishization of &hellip; <a href=\"http:\/\/book.hyko.org\/1970-06-12\/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&rarr;<\/span><\/a>",
