    "title": "Waiting for Your Life Online &sect; 1",
    "title_plain": "Waiting for Your Life Online &sect; 1",
    "content": "<p>For people who don&#8217;t like waiting, 1974 was a very good year. It was the year that Ed Roberts released the <!-- 404 ERROR ON THIS LINK a href=\"http:\/\/www.velocityguide.com\/computer-history\/altair-8800.html\" -->Altair 8800<!-- \/a -->,<strong>(REFERENCE ICON) In 1975 it was almost impossible for anyone outside Silicon Valley to find the necessary parts to build a computer. The Altair was offered as a complete kit, not just a list of parts. FURTHER READING \u201c<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pc-history.org\/altair.htm\">How the Altair Began<\/a>\u201d by Stan Veit.\u00a0<\/strong>a kit that let you build your own personal computer. And it was the year that the users of the Michigan Terminal System (MTS) <strong>(REFERENCE ICON) The Michigan Terminal System was one of the first time-sharing computer operating systems. FURTHER READING <a href=\"http:\/\/archive.michigan-terminal-system.org\/\">Michigan Terminal System Archive<\/a><\/strong> held their first workshop, just up the road from me at the University of British Columbia.<\/p>\n",
    "excerpt": "1974 was the beginning of the end for waiting, as home computer kits and time-sharing systems started to cut into all those hours waiting for the mainframe. Over the years, we wait less and less, as our computers and Internet connections and smartphones get better and better. But waiting may just be something worth waiting for. <a href=\"http:\/\/book.hyko.org\/1970-05-01\/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&rarr;<\/span><\/a>",
