    "id": 197304,
    "type": "post",
    "slug": "1970-04-04",
    "url": "http:\/\/book.hyko.org\/1970-04-04\/",
    "status": "publish",
    "title": "7 Rules for Rule-Breakers &sect; 4",
    "title_plain": "7 Rules for Rule-Breakers &sect; 4",
    "content": "<p>I&#8217;m talking about something more fundamental: the evasion of rules. &#8220;Pay for what you&#8217;re going to use&#8221; (read, listen to, watch) is one kind of rule that Internet users spend a lot of time getting around. But we also do a nice job of evading rules like age limitations (greetings, 11-year-olds on Facebook!), publication bans on court proceedings and even social norms (how many of the people who will tell someone to fuck themselves online would say the same thing face-to-face?) Sometimes it feels like the Internet&#8217;s slogan might as well be, &#8220;Oh yeah? Well c&#8217;mon over here and make me.&#8221;<\/p>\n",
    "excerpt": "I&#8217;m talking about something more fundamental: the evasion of rules. &#8220;Pay for what you&#8217;re going to use&#8221; (read, listen to, watch) is one kind of rule that Internet users spend a lot of time getting around. But we also do &hellip; <a href=\"http:\/\/book.hyko.org\/1970-04-04\/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&rarr;<\/span><\/a>",
