    "title": "Where You At? &sect; 2",
    "title_plain": "Where You At? &sect; 2",
    "content": "<p>But this technical innovation imposed a fundamentally social challenge. How would a computer distinguish between local messages and network messages? And how could you distinguish among users of different computers? While a local computer could only have a single user named jsmith, once you connected a couple of different computers to a network, each of them might have their own jsmith. Tomlinson needed a way to identify message senders and recipients not only by their usernames, but by the name of the computer that hosted their messages.<\/p>\n",
    "excerpt": "But this technical innovation imposed a fundamentally social challenge. How would a computer distinguish between local messages and network messages? And how could you distinguish among users of different computers? While a local computer could only have a single user &hellip; <a href=\"http:\/\/book.hyko.org\/1970-02-02\/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&rarr;<\/span><\/a>",
