    "id": 197106,
    "type": "post",
    "slug": "1970-02-06",
    "url": "http:\/\/book.hyko.org\/1970-02-06\/",
    "status": "publish",
    "title": "Where You At? &sect; 6",
    "title_plain": "Where You At? &sect; 6",
    "content": "<p>Once we transcend geography as the exclusive &#8212; or even primary &#8212; delimiter of community and identity, we change our relationship to location itself. &#8220;Where you at?&#8221; (now an idiom for &#8220;how are you doing?&#8221;) interrogates our mood, our well-being and the distribution of our attention as much as our physical location. I may be &#8220;at&#8221; my office, my house or an airport, but the conversations I am engaged in, the subject I am thinking about or the people I am interacting with can be anywhere in the world.<\/p>\n",
    "excerpt": "Once we transcend geography as the exclusive &#8212; or even primary &#8212; delimiter of community and identity, we change our relationship to location itself. &#8220;Where you at?&#8221; (now an idiom for &#8220;how are you doing?&#8221;) interrogates our mood, our well-being &hellip; <a href=\"http:\/\/book.hyko.org\/1970-02-06\/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&rarr;<\/span><\/a>",
