    "title_plain": "Where You At? &sect; 8",
    "content": "<p>But the demise of the literal &#8220;at&#8221; challenges us to not only transcend geography, but to rethink and perhaps reclaim it. The emergence of a global economy and supply chain &#8212; a development that is inextricable from the enabling infrastructure of the Internet &#8212; has given birth to the relocalization movement, focused on eating and shopping locally. Local community networks, which came into existence as a way of providing low-cost Internet access, have been reborn as hubs for supporting the effective use of technology as a resource for community renewal. Location-based social networks like FourSquare and Facebook check-ins have turned our digital @s into physical ats: by connecting my FourSquare account with my Twitter account, I can find out where my Twitter pals are checking in, and seek them out face-to-face.<\/p>\n",
    "excerpt": "But the demise of the literal &#8220;at&#8221; challenges us to not only transcend geography, but to rethink and perhaps reclaim it. The emergence of a global economy and supply chain &#8212; a development that is inextricable from the enabling infrastructure &hellip; <a href=\"http:\/\/book.hyko.org\/1970-02-08\/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&rarr;<\/span><\/a>",
