    "title": "Where You At? &sect; 12",
    "title_plain": "Where You At? &sect; 12",
    "content": "<p>If you can be @ anywhere in the world, and still find the online work and communities of your choice, how do you decide where to be at? It&#8217;s useful to think of at and @ as complements; as the yin and yang of your personal ecosystem. If where you are at &#8212; the place you live offline &#8212; is a deeply nourishing neighbourhood or town that you&#8217;ve chosen because it&#8217;s the mirror of your soul, then you may need to spend more time @ communities that challenge you to think differently: reading online articles, engaging in online conversations and participating in online collaborations that bring you into contact with people and ideas that are different from your own. Conversely, if your online life consists of long hours of chatting or gaming with your fellow left-handed vegan crafters, you may appreciate the breadth you gain by living in an offline community that tugs against the natural grain of your personality.<\/p>\n",
    "excerpt": "If you can be @ anywhere in the world, and still find the online work and communities of your choice, how do you decide where to be at? It&#8217;s useful to think of at and @ as complements; as the &hellip; <a href=\"http:\/\/book.hyko.org\/1970-02-12\/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&rarr;<\/span><\/a>",
