    "title_plain": "Creating an Archive and Roadmap of the Digital Revolution &sect; 2",
    "content": "<p>Judged as prose, these two sentences can&#8217;t hold a candle to what you&#8217;d read on Boing Boing, Mashable or ReadWriteWeb today. But these lines come from the literary grandfather of today&#8217;s self-documenting Internet: a 1970 paper titled &#8220;<a href=\"http:\/\/www.packet.cc\/files\/comp-net-dev.html\">Computer network development to achieve resource sharing<\/a>.&#8221;\u00a0Written by Lawrence Roberts and Barry Wesser, it was the first paper to document the newly-minted ARPAnet. As such, it ushered in one of the chief occupations of the Internet era: documenting the evolution of the network itself.<\/p>\n",
    "excerpt": "Judged as prose, these two sentences can&#8217;t hold a candle to what you&#8217;d read on Boing Boing, Mashable or ReadWriteWeb today. But these lines come from the literary grandfather of today&#8217;s self-documenting Internet: a 1970 paper titled &#8220;Computer network development &hellip; <a href=\"http:\/\/book.hyko.org\/1970-01-02\/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&rarr;<\/span><\/a>",
